# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Misconceptions
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:misconception-romans-allowed-prasutagus-boudica-rule
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All Romans allowed Prasutagus and Boudica rule the east of England."@en ;
  curric:correction """When Prasutagus died, the Roman Emperor Nero did not want to share power and
  control of the land with Boudica and her daughters."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.084783Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-england-defeated-spain
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think England defeated Spain easily with their Navy."@en ;
  curric:correction """It was a combination of factors that allowed England to defeat Spain
  including being helped by the weather."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.085049Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-anglo-saxons-one-king-britain
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Anglo-Saxons only had one king in Britain."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Anglo-Saxons had different kingdoms in Britain, each with its own
  king."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089598Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-believe-victorian-children-worked
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may believe that all Victorian children worked, or that no Victorian
  children had an education."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Children from wealthy families were educated at home or sent to schools that
  were paid for. Some children went to small local schools on some days of the week and
  worked on other days. Some of the least fortunate children did not go to school at all."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089959Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-athelstan-controlled-scotland
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that Athelstan controlled Scotland because he defeated
  Constantine."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Although Constantine lost, Athelstan only remained king of England. He became
  overlord of Scotland but failed to unite England and Scotland under one kingship."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090110Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-suleiman-lawgiver-suleiman-magnificent
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some may think that 'Suleiman the Lawgiver' and 'Suleiman the Magnificent' are
  different people."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that these are different names used for the same person to remember
  different elements of his time as Sultan of the Ottoman Empire."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091403Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-eleanor-louis-married-long
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that Eleanor and Louis were not married for very long."@en ;
  curric:correction """Eleanor and Louis were married for 15 years before their marriage was
  annulled by the church."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092157Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-emperor-jah-ng
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think Emperor Jahāngīr was angry with Nūr Jahān for becoming
  powerful."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to pupils that Emperor Jahāngīr admired Nūr Jahān and was grateful to
  her for looking after him and taking care of his responsibilities while he was ill."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092176Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-inventions-things-like-machines-robots
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That inventions are always things like machines, robots, computers and
  so on."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Inventions come from ideas, and people can have ideas about so many different
  situations in life. The invention here for example is a type of pain relief for
  childbirth, a medical invention."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.093634Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-snakes-used-live-ireland
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That snakes used to live in Ireland."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that snakes were unlikely to have ever lived in Ireland due to the
  geography and climate. It is thought that the snakes in the story of St. Patrick and the
  snakes of Ireland were a metaphor or symbol."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.094315Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-st-patrick-irish
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That St. Patrick was Irish."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to children that St. Patrick was born in Britain. As a teenager, he
  was captured by raiders and taken to Ireland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.094328Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-one-legend-boudica
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think there can only be one legend about Boudica."@en ;
  curric:correction """There are many legends about Boudica's death. Historians from the past have
  told different stories but we do not know which is the truth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.094807Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-legends-true
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That legends are true."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure children understand that legends are stories that are often told
  verbally and may change over time. Play a game to demonstrate this; children sit in a
  circle and pass a message around by whispering to each other. Does the messgae change?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.094853Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-robert-bruce-fictional-character-story
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Robert the Bruce is a fictional character in a story."@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure that children understand that Robert the Bruce was a real person from
  the past."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.095479Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-south-africa-refers-southern-half
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That 'South Africa' refers to the southern half of the continent of
  Africa."""@en ;
  curric:correction """'South Africa' is one single African country, which is located in the south
  of the continent of Africa. The south of africa (the part that sits in the southern
  hemisphere) covers a much larger area and includes 15 other individual African countries."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.096337Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confused-emperor-20-wives
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may be confused by the emperor having 20 wives."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to pupils that in some countries and some religions you can marry
  multiple people. However today in the UK, it is illegal to marry more than one person."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.097103Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-welsh-lords-chanting-owain-glyndwr
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The Welsh lords were chanting 'Owain Glyndwr, Prince of Wales' because he was
  the Prince."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Ensure children know that the Welsh lords were chanting because they wanted
  Owain to become the Prince of Wales and their leader."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.098842Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-struggle-fact-united-kingdom
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils can struggle with the fact that the United Kingdom is a country made up
  of four separate smaller countries. Furthermore we also refer to Great Britain - which can
  again be confusing for pupils."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The UK's full name is The United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern
  Ireland. England, Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland make up the UK. Great Britain is
  only the mainland countries of England, Wales and Scotland that share land borders."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.099317Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-life-same-750-years-ago
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That life was the same 750 years ago as it is today."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to children that lots of things were very different 750 years ago.
  For example, there were no cars, planes or trains and it would have taken Owain a long
  time to travel to Scotland and London. People would have travelled by horse or walked."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.099334Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-failure-capture-vienna-meant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some may think that the failure to capture Vienna meant Suleiman was a
  failure."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emphasise that setbacks are normal and Suleiman was still able to extend the
  Ottoman Empire to its greatest ever reach."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101083Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-church-same-church-building
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that the Church is the same as a church building."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Church is the name of the organisation that includes all the people who
  lead the Christian religion. Buildings are also called churches."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101154Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-johns-sisters-line-throne
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some may think that John's sisters would be in line to the throne
  before him."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that this is the case today in the UK - Princess Charlotte became the
  first female royal to benefit from The Succession to the Crown Act in 2013. The Act stated
  that girls born into the Royal Family will not be overtaken by younger brothers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101245Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-classes-society-small
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that classes in society are small groups, like classes at
  school."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Classes are groups of people, but classes in society include thousands,
  sometimes millions of people and they are not age related like school classes, they depend
  on other factors like wealth or profession."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101440Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-kings-queens-king-john
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some may think that kings and queens after King John forgot about
  Magna Carta."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Kings and queens after King John still followed Magna Carta and it remained
  as a very important document of rights for the people. Today, there are still four of the
  original 63 clauses in use in England."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101616Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-confuse-term-caravan
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may confuse the term caravan."@en ;
  curric:correction "Explain to pupils that a group of camels is called a caravan."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101630Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-musa-keita-meant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think Musa Keita was meant to be mansa."@en ;
  curric:correction """Musa Keita became mansa because the previous mansa did not return from his
  voyage and he chose Musa Keita to replace him."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101639Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-kings-queens-needed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think all kings and queens needed to be married."@en ;
  curric:correction """Elizabeth decided she didn’t want to marry and she proved that she didn’t
  need to be to be a successful queen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101954Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-names-aethelflaed-aethelred-similar-mistaken
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The names Aethelflaed and Aethelred are very similar and may be mistaken for
  the same person."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Highlight that the two names are very similar but that Aethelflaed was the
  daughter of Alfred the Great and became Lady of Mercia, whereas Aethelred was the king of
  the Anglo-Saxon kingdom of Mercia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.102648Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-aquitaine-same-modern-day
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that Aquitaine is the same as modern day France."@en ;
  curric:correction """Aquitaine was only one area of modern day France, there were lots of areas
  controlled by different powerful families at this time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.102813Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-buildings-commissioned-suleiman-used
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some may think that the buildings commissioned by Suleiman are not used or in
  existence today."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Many of them still exist 500 years later and can be seen today, particularly
  the mosques and religious buildings which have been continually renovated over time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.103001Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-britain-still-rules
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that Britain still rules over or controls India today."@en ;
  curric:correction """Britain does not rule India today. Britain ruled India and much of the
  surrounding land for over 300 years, but this ended in 1947 when the territory was
  partitioned into two separate independent countries which became India and Pakistan."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.103281Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-muslims-pilgrimage
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think all Muslims have to do the pilgrimage."@en ;
  curric:correction """The pilgrimage is something many Muslims would like to do. However, it is
  only required if they are able to do it. Travelling to Mecca is too expensive for many
  people. Others might not be physically able to do the pilgrimage."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105382Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-mehr-al-nes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think Mehr al-Nesā sitting next to a snake is completely true."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to the pupils that Mehr al-Nesā's early life is still unknown. There
  are only legends about her story. A legend is a traditional story that might not always be
  true."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105388Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-paul-stephensons-actions-directly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some may think that only Paul Stephenson's actions directly led to the 1965
  law."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Paul's actions had an impact as did many other people's in the 1960s."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.106421Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-militant-tactics-good
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some children might think that militant tactics are a good way for them to get
  the things that they want to."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The Suffragettes used extreme tactics because they felt that it was their
  only option. Going on hunger strike is dangerous. For the issues that children might face,
  there are many safer and less harmful ways to make a change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.106426Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-women-allowed-go-university
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some may think that women were not allowed to go to university at all in
  Victorian Britain."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Women were allowed to study at university, work very hard and take all of the
  same exams as men, but they were not allowed the degree at the end of it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.107140Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-emily-davison-quit-her
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that Emily Davison quit her job to join the Suffragettes."@en ;
  curric:correction """Emily joined the Suffragettes in 1906 and did not quit her job to fight for
  women's suffrage full time until 1908."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.107195Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-coronation-ceremony-person-becomes-monarch
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That a coronation ceremony is when a person becomes a monarch."@en ;
  curric:correction """The person who is first in line to the throne becomes monarch the minute that
  the previous monarch passes away. It happens in an instant. The coronation is an official
  ceremony, held later where the monarch receives their crown in front of people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.107252Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-emily-davison-paul-stephenson
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some may think that Emily Davison and Paul Stephenson were fighting for the
  same thing."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Emily Davison and Paul Stephenson were fighting for different change to
  happen in Britain at different times, around 50 years apart."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.107674Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-evacuation-negative-experience-children
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That evacuation was a negative experience for all children."@en ;
  curric:correction """Lots of children had healthier diets, more freedom and enjoyed their lives in
  the countryside."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.107917Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-soon-someone-arrested-go
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that as soon as someone is arrested, they go to prison."@en ;
  curric:correction """This doesn't happen and is not what happened to Paul Stephenson. He was kept
  in a holding cell in the police station until midnight."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.108475Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-people-came-britain-caribbean
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that people only came to Britain from the Caribbean."@en ;
  curric:correction """People from all over the world came to Britain, including from places like
  India and Poland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109292Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-emily-davison-died-day
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that Emily Davison died on the day of the Epsom Derby."@en ;
  curric:correction """Emily Davison died four days after the race at Epsom, on the 8th of June
  1913."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.109298Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-certain-jobs-men-women
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That certain jobs are for men only or women only."@en ;
  curric:correction "Just like during the war, anyone should be able to and can do any job."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110965Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-eleanor-prisoner-kept-terrible
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think of Eleanor as a prisoner being kept in terrible conditions."@en ;
  curric:correction """Eleanor lived in places of comfort, for example, castles. She did not have
  the freedom to leave but was well looked after."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.111764Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-relics-st-columba
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think the relics of St Columba were valuable."@en ;
  curric:correction """The relics of St Columba were an important symbol of the Christian faith
  throughout the kingdom of Alba."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.111828Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-crystal-palace-still
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that the Crystal Palace is still standing or that it can be
  seen or visited today."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The Crystal Palace was a temporary structure built for the exhibition. It was
  relocated and rebuilt in another part of London but was later destroyed by fire. The
  surrounding area was then named Crystal Palace to show how important the structure was."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112198Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-victoria-albert-married-because-made
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That Victoria and Albert only married because they were made to do so, not
  because they loved each other."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Victoria and Albert had a strong connection from the first time they met.
  Written evidence tells us that the two were very much in love and their marriage was a
  happy, loving relationship."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112255Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-elizabeth-right-throne
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think Elizabeth had a right to the throne when her father Henry
  VIII died."""@en ;
  curric:correction """At this time, the heir to the throne was the first-born son of the King
  rather than the first-born child."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112295Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-queen-victoria-died-queen-elizabeth
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That when Queen Victoria died, then Queen Elizabeth II became queen."@en ;
  curric:correction """There were other monarchs in between Queen Victoria and Queen Elizabeth II.
  Queen Elizabeth II was the next female monarch but she did not become queen until 50 years
  after Queen Victoria died."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112484Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-revenge-involves-killing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think revenge always involves killing people."@en ;
  curric:correction """Revenge is the act of getting back at someone for something they did to you.
  This may involve stealing something or destroying something like property."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112630Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-women-able-lead
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think women were not able to lead rebellions."@en ;
  curric:correction """Boudica was a strong leader and the tribes respected her. The tribes were
  happy to follow her as part of the rebellion against the Romans."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112768Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-inside-places-like-inside-boats
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Inside places (like inside boats) are warmer than outside places."@en ;
  curric:correction """Inside places have shelter from rain, so they're drier, but not necessarily
  warmer. If a place is cold, everywhere is cold unless heated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.114530Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-race-across-atlantic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that the 'race across the Atlantic' was an actual race, like
  on school sports day."""@en ;
  curric:correction """At around the same time, people in different places were trying to achieve
  the same thing, so whoever achieved it first won the 'race'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.114873Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-find-confusing-john-cabot
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might find it confusing that John Cabot sounds like a very English name
  yet he was Italian."""@en ;
  curric:correction """John Cabot is the English version of the name he was born as, Giovanni
  Caboto. He lived in England for so long he was known by John Cabot."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.114879Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-impression-vikings-fierce-scary
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may have the impression that all Vikings were fierce, scary
  warriors."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Some Vikings were warriors, but not all. Vikings were also traders, farmers
  and settlers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116213Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-because-european-seafarers
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think because European seafarers were using the navigation tools,
  they invented them too."""@en ;
  curric:correction """European seafarers didn't invent the astrolabe or compass. Many ancient
  people navigated by the stars like the Polynesians and Vikings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116478Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-explorers-use-map
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that explorers always use a map."@en ;
  curric:correction """Early explorers did not have maps. They often used natural features to
  navigate by such as rivers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116864Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-chinese-ships-engines
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Chinese ships must have had engines."@en ;
  curric:correction """Engines had not been invented yet. Chinese sailing ships relied on the wind
  and power of the sea to make long journeys."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117249Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-polynesia-country
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that Polynesia is a country."@en ;
  curric:correction """Polynesia is not one single country. It is a large area of the Pacific Ocean
  containing lots of different islands."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117257Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-mediterranean-single-country
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that the Mediterranean is a single country."@en ;
  curric:correction """The Mediterranean is a large area surrounding and including the Mediterranean
  Sea. Many countries are part of this area."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117880Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-looking-2d-map-world-pupils
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When looking at a 2D map of the world, pupils may think that there are two
  Pacific oceans."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The Pacific Ocean is the biggest ocean on earth. We can see on a globe that
  it is one large body of water between the Americas and Asia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117897Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-past-ships-carried
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that in the past ships only carried sailors, captains or
  other people working on the ship."""@en ;
  curric:correction """About 200 years ago, people began to travel through choice. People that
  travel on ships but do not work on them are called passengers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119099Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-oceans-totally-distinct
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that the oceans are totally distinct, separate bodies of
  water."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Large bodies of water like oceans and seas are connected by smaller bodies of
  water like rivers. You can sail from one ocean to another."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119883Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-ship-called-fighting-temeraire
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that the ship was called 'The Fighting Temeraire'."@en ;
  curric:correction """'The Fighting Temeraire' was the name of Turner's painting, the ship was
  called HMS Temeraire."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.125453Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-zheng-went-his
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that Zheng He went on his voyages by himself."@en ;
  curric:correction """He was admiral of the Chinese fleet. He took many ships and lots of sailors
  on the voyages."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.129543Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-adults-worked-jobs
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that only adults worked at jobs in factories in Victorian
  times."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In Victorian times, there were no laws stopping children working. Children
  had to earn money to live, so many of them worked in factories. Since they were young and
  small, children were useful for getting into tight spaces to clean or fix machines."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.140825Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-nothing-known-victoria-indeed-other
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That nothing is known about Victoria (or indeed other monarchs) before
  becoming Queen."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There is a lot of historical evidence about Victoria's childhood including
  written accounts and artefacts that tell us a great deal about what her early life was
  like."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.143758Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-archaeologists-dig-bones
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that archaeologists only dig up bones, like dinosaurs or
  extinct creatures."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Archaeologists work with all sorts of objects from the past, many of the
  items in museums have been dug up by an archaeologist."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.147036Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-early-astronomy-conducted
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that most early astronomy was conducted using telescopes."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that astronomers didn’t have telescopes, so they used their
  eyes and mathematical calculations to help them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155209Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-marie-worked-herself
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that Marie worked by herself."@en ;
  curric:correction "Remind pupils that she worked closely with her husband."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155218Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-lovelace-built-first
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that Lovelace built the first working computer."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that Ada did not build a real computer, but she did write
  clever notes and ideas explaining how Babbage’s machine could work, even though it was
  never finished. Her imagination helped people understand the first ideas of a computer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155227Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-sophia-won-women
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some pupils may think that Sophia won women the vote all by herself."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that many brave women worked together for many years to win the
  right to vote, and Sophia was just one important part of that team."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155239Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-mandela-ended-apartheid
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that Mandela ended apartheid on his own."@en ;
  curric:correction "Remind pupils that he worked with many others to change the laws."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155248Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-people-past-believed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might think that people in the past always believed sickness came from
  bad spirits or punishment."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind them that, despite not having our modern scientific understanding of
  illness and medicine, people in the past knew a great deal about sickness and helping ill
  people, and worked carefully to discover as much as they could."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155254Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-trains-same-victorian-times-today
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Trains were the same in the Victorian times as today."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that the trains in the Victorian times were run on steam. They would
  have been very dirty, noisy and bumpy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155724Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-people-able-take
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may assume that people have always been able to take photographs."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that photography was invented 200 years ago and, before that,
  photographs did not exist. People would have drawn or painted to record what they could
  see in front of them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155751Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-second-world-war-happening-1950s
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The Second World War was happening in the 1950's."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to the children that the Second World War ended half way through the
  1940's. In the 1950's people and cities were recovering from the effects of the war. New
  houses, technology and transport was available."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155778Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-people-past-used
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may assume that people in the past used phones and tablets to take
  photographs."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Show pupils the various devices that have been used in the past to take
  photographs and how they have evolved."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155784Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-photographs-way-find-1960s-1970s
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That photographs are the only way to find out about the 1960s and 1970s."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that photographs are one source that historians can use. They also
  look at written evidence such as newspaper articles and diaries. They can talk to people
  who were alive in the 1960s and 1970s and look at artefacts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155792Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-families-same-140-years-ago
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That all families were the same 140 years ago and life was the same for
  everyone."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain that while the photograph gives us some clues to life in the past,
  just like now, all families were different."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155818Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-elizabeth-iis-choice
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that Elizabeth II's choice of clothes was just to
  look nice."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that her clothes were part of her work. They showed duty and
  respect wherever she went."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.158015Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-people-see-elizabeth
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils might think that people could see Elizabeth during her broadcast."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind them that television was not ubiquitous at this time in Britain, and
  the radio broadcast only delivered sound."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.158673Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-coronation-royal-wedding
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils might think a coronation and a royal wedding are the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Explain to pupils that although both events are full of pagentry and
  symbolism and take place in a religious setting, these are just similarities and does not
  mean they are the same thing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.160364Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-elizabeth-fought-war
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils might think that Elizabeth fought in the war."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that when war began she was still a child; her job was to stay
  safe and learn how to be a future queen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.161494Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-elizabeth-ii-lived
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might think that Elizabeth II only lived, and stayed, in London (maybe
  at Buckingham Palace)."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Show and remind pupils how Elizabeth II travelled across the UK and around
  the world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162242Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-thousands-people-attend-funerals
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some may think that thousands of people attend funerals usually."@en ;
  curric:correction """Emily Davison's funeral was an exception. Usually funerals are only attended
  by people who knew the person."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162427Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-queen-elizabeth-ii
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils might think that Queen Elizabeth II is still alive."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that she died in 2022, but we remember her life and
  service."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163158Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-think-people-allowed-work-bristol
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Some may think that the only people not allowed to work for the Bristol bus
  companies in 1963 were black people."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The bus companies did not allow anyone who was not white to work for
  them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164838Z"^^xsd:dateTime .
